The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New Delhi, July 3: The Central Electricity Regulatory Commission (CERC) has threatened to cancel licences of 13 companies, including the National Thermal Power Corporation, Tata Power, Reliance Energy and PTC India. It is upset over their non-compliance of licence agreement for inter-state trading in power. The CERC has rapped the trading companies for not submitting the required information every quarter to the regulator and has issued notices asking them to cite reasons as to why their licences should not be revoked.

 New Delhi, July 3: The coal ministry will place its plans to augment coal production before the environment ministry next week for its approval. The ministry plans to raise coal output by 20-25 million tonnes over and above the approved capacity from its existing mines. It has already launched a crisis management programme to tide over the shortage of coal due to rise in demand from power and sponge-iron sectors.

 New Delhi, July 3: The government will ensure adequate expenditure by ministries and departments throughout the year so that bulk of the fund is not spent in the last quarter, said expenditure secretary Adarsh Kishore.

 Calcutta, July 3: IBP Ltd will invest around Rs 500 crore during this fiscal to fund the expansion of retail outlets as well as modernisation of the existing ones, sources said.

 New Delhi, July 3: The Confederation of Indian Industry has mooted the idea of promoting monsoon tourism in the country to provide a fillip to the tourism sector beyond the traditional seasons.

 New Delhi, July 3: Panacea Biotech will set up three plants and add four research and development centres. It is also planning a foray into the US and European markets by 2008.

 New Delhi, July 3: Exports of agricultural and allied products have recorded an increase of over 9 per cent at Rs 27,111.41 crore ($6.03 billion) in 2004-05 against Rs 24,844.48 crore ($5.4 billion) in the previous financial year.




